# planning-dependent-issue-unverified-upstream -- History

## v1.1.0 (2026-06-20)

**Changed by:** ProjectArgus issue #153 re-plan after NOGO (grade C)
**Verification:** unverified (still a PLAN; no docker build / CI ran — but the gh/git inspection commands WERE run and are real)

### What changed
- **Corrected the central recommendation.** v1.0.0 advised "front-load dependency verification + provide inline conditional fallbacks." This session proved the *second half is a trap*: a dependent issue's upstream is almost always ALREADY MERGED and READABLE, and reading it collapses every "if the dependency did X else Y" fork into one concrete fact. The fallbacks were not just clutter — several were WRONG, and only reading the merged code revealed it. The new guidance is **verify the MERGED dependency code and ELIMINATE the forks**, not write fallbacks around guesses.
- Reworked Detailed Step 3 from "state a conditional fallback inline next to every assumption" to "read the merged dependency and replace every if/else fork with one verified path." Added explicit commands to find and read the merged branch.
- Added the concrete verification commands that worked this session to Quick Reference:
  - `gh pr list --repo <r> --state merged --search "152 in:body OR 152 in:title" --json number,title,headRefName` (find the merged dependency PR + its head branch)
  - `git fetch origin && git ls-tree -r --name-only origin/<branch> | grep '^dashboard/'` (full merged file tree — even when the local submodule is pinned to an older SHA on a detached HEAD)
  - `git show origin/<branch>:dashboard/go.mod` / `:routes.go` / `:main.go` (read the real module path, go/toolchain version, signatures, existing handlers)
- Added five new Failed Attempts rows, one per WRONG fallback the prior guidance would have produced (wrong module path, golang:1.22 vs go.mod's go 1.23/toolchain 1.24, illegal `//go:embed` parent path, healthz exists-but-returns-wrong-body, atlas.css already-exists scope bleed).
- Bumped version 1.0.0 -> 1.1.0; added `history:` frontmatter field; updated `date` to 2026-06-20; refreshed description to warn against the conditional-fallback anti-pattern and point at reading merged code.

### Why
This was a SECOND `/learn` pass on the dependent-issue planning theme. The first plan for #153 (built with v1.0.0's advice) drew a NOGO (grade C) for two MAJOR findings: (1) "stage handoff" — steps were conditional on UNVERIFIED dependency (#152) output, handing the implementer a decision tree of forks instead of a concrete build sequence; (2) "P2/YAGNI cross-boundary scope" — it contingently planned to create files (atlas.css, /healthz, server Assets field) that actually belonged to the dependency. The re-plan fixed it by reading the actually-merged dependency code (PR #160, branch `feat/issue-152-atlas-bootstrap`). The conditional fallbacks v1.0.0 recommended would have encoded:
  - module `github.com/HomericIntelligence/ProjectArgus/dashboard` — WRONG; real module is `github.com/HomericIntelligence/atlas` (the `-X` ldflags path was wrong)
  - builder `golang:1.22-alpine` (the issue's literal text) — WRONG; go.mod declares `go 1.23.0` + `toolchain go1.24.2`, so 1.22 FAILS the build (must be `golang:1.24-alpine`)
  - `//go:embed web` in `main.go` — ILLEGAL; `web/` is at `dashboard/web/` and main.go at `dashboard/cmd/argus-dashboard/`; Go's `//go:embed` cannot reference parent dirs, so the embed file must be co-located: `dashboard/web/embed.go` (package `web`, exporting `web.Static`)
  - "add /healthz if missing" — MISSED that it existed but returned plain text `"ok"` while the acceptance criterion required `{"status":"ok"}` JSON
  - "create atlas.css if missing" — scope bleed; it already existed (62 lines) and must NOT be recreated
These are durable, reusable planning lessons (not specific to Dockerfiles), so they are folded into the skill rather than discarded.

